Walker was democratically elected in a free and fair contest and then proceeded to mount an anti-union agenda that horrified his opponents. Fair enough. If the state's residents didn't like it, they could lobby their state legislators to overrule the governor, or start mounting a campaign to defeat him in the next election. Instead, they began a recall effort – winning by getting enough signatures to have a recall election, then losing by failing to recall him. Polls at the time showed that some residents simply didn't like the idea of a recall – and they have a strong point.
